  urldate = {2026-03-12},
  abstract = {In this work, we study the quantum confinement (QC) effect on the Schottky barrier height (\textbackslash Phi\_\textbackslash textSB) of various metals on atomically thin In2O3 channels for the first time. A positive-to-negative \textbackslash Phi\_\textbackslash textSB conversion is experimentally observed by increasing the In2O3 channel thickness Tch from 1.2 to 1.6 nm and above, which can be understood by QC and Fermi-level pinning (FLP) effects. To support the above understanding, FLP in metal/In2O3 contacts is also investigated for the first time by extracting the \textbackslash Phi\_\textbackslash textSB and pinning factor S. The close-to-zero S parameters between 0.024 - 0.004 verify the strong FLP at the metal/In2O3 interfaces. The contact with negative \textbackslash Phi\_\textbackslash textSB highlights the uniqueness of In2O3 versus other conventional semiconductors, such as Si, Ge, and monolayer MoS2, whose Fermi-level are pinned with positive \textbackslash Phi\_\textbackslash textSB.},
